The paper deals with error-correcting codes and their decoding algorithms, which are typically studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and computational complexity (cs.CC) sub-categories. The use of expanders and unique games algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the discrete mathematics (cs.DS) and computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on combinatorial properties and their potential for coding theoretic constructions suggests that it may also be relevant to the cryptography (cs.CR) sub-category.
